		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailTitle" style="text-align:center;">
                            Summary on Grant Application Form</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailValue" style="padding:5px;">
                        <span id="lblAbstract">The statistical properties of flows have notoriously been difficult to deal with.  Some progress has been made very recently for some classes of flows which do not include the examples we have in mind, through non-trivial generalisations of relatively classical functional-analytic techniques.We aim to take a quite different approach, in the spirit of a recent breakthrough of LS Young in the study of rates of mixing and decay of correlations for discrete dynamical systems.  She uses a more geometric and probabilistic argument which I believe can be generalised to the case of continuous time dynamical systems, ie flows.  In this case a further  Holder  regularity condition on the return times of trajectories will need to be assumed.We then intend to verify that the required conditions are satisfied in important classes of examples such as the Lorenz attractor.</span>
                        </td>
		</tr>
